{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_jackpot_ver01/data/sn86091313/00332891315/1908011701/0013.xml":{"full_text":"ooc>oooooooooooooo\nTHE LOVELOCK TRIBUNEf\nQ CHERRY A PEARSON. Prop*. Q\nooooooooooooooooo\nPublished every Friday.\nteredat the Lovelock*, Nev., Poatofflce,\nfor transmission through the mails as\nSeound-elasa matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nfine Year, by mail, in United States, $3.00\nSix Montli*.. 1-50\nThree Month ,\"5\nForeign Oflleea\u2014 Postage additional.\nADVERTISING RATES:\nLo uis Ten cents per line each insertion.\nDisplay Ada\u2014$1 per inch per month single\ncolumn.\nI.egul Notices At regular Legal Rates.\nFRIDAY. JANUARY 17, 1908\nt\nPROSPECTS NEVER BRIGHTER\nA prominent citizen of Lovelock,\nwho hag resided in this great valley\nfor a number of years, and who is\nas well posted as anyone both as to\nthe agricultural and mining indus\ntries, was heard to sav recently that\nthe future outlook for Lovelock and\nthe numerous surrounding mining\ndistricts never looked better. He\npredicted that in the present year,\n1908, Lovelock would witness one of\nthe greatest booms ever experienced\nsince the founding of the town.\nEverything points to the predicion\nbecoming a fact. While it is true\nwe are just emerging from a financial\npanic which has effected the country\nover, business in Lovelock for the\nfirst few weeks in the new year has\nshown a decided increase. With\nconfidence restored and with the vast\nagricultural resources in this valley\ntogether with the rich mineral dis\ntricts which are te bo found on all\nsides, and which are tributary to this\ntown, Lovelock\u2019s future is indeed very\nbright.\nKKEI\u2019 HIM OUT\nIt is reported that overtures have\nbeen made or will be made, by the\nmine owners of Goldfield, to have\nSherman Bell, who had charge of the\nfield operations of the Colorado state\ntroops during the \u201cPeabody war,\u201d go\nto the southern camp, organize a\nNational guard and take charge of\nthe strike situation in that camp.\nBell is reported to have said he\nwould go if asked and was duly com\npensated.\nKeep him out. Goldfield has enough\n\u201chot heads\u201d now, and the importa\ntion of such a man as Bell would only\ntend to make matters worse. The\nmine owners are pursuing the right\ncourse and the radicals among the\nWestern Federation will soon have\nthe \u201cskidoo 23\" tied to them. BjII\nis very unpopular with both sides and\nit is a moral certainty that if he\nwont to Goldfield bloodshed would\nresult.\nto IT tit I\u2019lfUHPBITS\nFor some time past there has been\ndeveloping a tidal wave of discontent\nbetween the smaller mines and the\nAmerican Smelting and Kefii ing Co.,\nas a result of the arbitrary manner\nin which oro treatment charges are\nregulated.\nRecently a report circulated that\nthe smaller mine owners of Butte,\nHelena and other sections of Montana\nwere organizing for the purpose of\ncontesting the agreement which is\nalleged to have been made between\nthe American Smelting and Refining\nCo. and the Amalgamated Copper Co.\nThis agreement, it is contended,\nhas been the means of advancing ore\ntreatment charges at Fast Helena\nand Creat Falls over 50 per cent.\nIn consequence of this agreement,\nit is claimed, the smaller mines have\nbeen practically forced to stop work.\nThe ore treatment charges may be\nprohibitory to the successful working\nof the smaller mines at current prices\nfor copper; but to attribute the initial\ncause to the alleged statement of W.\nA. ('lark that the small miners and\nlow-grade producers would never\nagain be permitted to operate or\nbreak the copper market by the over\nproduction, is, to say the least, rather\nfar fetched. We can hardly believe\nthat Mr. Clark could be guilty of\nmaking such a rash statement in pub\nlic, for the reasos that he is too well\ninformed as regards the actual con\nditions of the copper industry.\nIf any one can be held Responsible\nfor the heavy fall in the price\nof copper it is the class of\nsellers who at first so unwisely \u201cpeg\nged\" the quotation at an extraordi\nnary high level. No one man can be\nsaid to have precipitated the present I\ndemoralization in the copper mining\nindustry, the (dis) honor, if such it\ncan be called, must be shared by a\ncoterie of men who should have known\nbetter.\nJuBt now, after two or three\nmonths of retrenchment in produc\ntion and \u2018'housecleaning,\u201d the copper\ntrade is assuming a somewhat better\natmospheric appearance. Prices show\na fractional recovery, and with easier\nmoney even the copper share market\nis improving. Sometime ago we sug\ngested that the price of the metal\nwould eventually be held around 14\nor 15 cents per lb. So far there has\nbeen no reason to change our early\nopinion; and if we mistake not, the\nundercurrent in the copper market\nwill lead to continued improvement.\n\u2014Mining World.\nNOTICE TO TRESPASSERS\nHunting or shooting on the Reser\nvation Ranch is strictly forbidden.\nAny person found trespassing will\nbe prosecuted to the full extent of\nthe law.\nGEORGE WEBB, Manager.\nPROFESSIONAL CARDS\nJ)R. J. P. MARTIN\nPhysician and Surgeon\nOffice over Drug Store, Residence opposite\nSchool House, Marker Addition\n(\u2019alls for Town or Valley, Night or Day,\nPromptly Attended\nJ)R. W. M. SCOTT\nPhysician and Surgeon\nSurgical Cases and Pneumonia a Specialty\nCalls Promptly Answered Day or Night\nOffice at Residence.\nJ)R. F. M. WEST\nPhysician and Surgeon\nSpecial Attention Given to Diseases of\nWomen and Children\nTown or Valley (\u2019alls Promptly Answered\nDay or Night\nOffice: Joe Therien Residence\nJ)R. S. E. D. PINNIGER\nPhysician and Surgeon\nLovelock Nevada\nE. MORRISON\nDentist\nAll Riuds of First-Class Dental Work at\nReasonable Prices\nOffice: Over Drug Store\nLovelock Nevada\nL G. CAMPBELL\nAttorney-at-Law\nOffice\u2014Lovelock Mercantile Company\nBuilding,\nLovelock Nevada\nJ A. CALLAHAN\nAttorney-at-Law\nCorporations Organized, General Law Busi\nness Dil